<exercises xml:id="ex-uSubstitution">
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <m>u</m>-substitution integration method was designed to undo a specific derivative rule. Explain.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <m>u</m>-substitution integration method deals with composition of functions. If you're looking at a composite function <m>f(g(x))</m>, how do you identify the <q>inside</q> function, <m>g(x)</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each composite function <m>f(g(x))</m> below, identify two different possibilities for both the <q>inside</q> <m>g(x)</m> function and the <q>outside</q> <m>f(x)</m> function.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(g(x)) = \sqrt{x^2+1}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(g(x)) = \sin(e^x+1)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(g(x)) = e^{\cos(x)}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(g(x)) = (\tan(x)+x)^6</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the chain rule to differentiate each of the following. Carefully note for each problem which part of the composite function acts as the <q>inside</q>piece.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{e^{x^2}}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{\ln(\sin(x))}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{-\cos(\sqrt{x})}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{(5x+1)^{10}}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{\tan(e^x+\pi)}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\Ddx{\sqrt{x^3+1}}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Integrate the following indefinite integrals using the suggested <m>u</m>-substitution.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int 2xe^{x^2}\;dx</m>; <m>u = x^2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)}\right)\;dx</m>; <m>u = \sin(x)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{\sin(\sqrt{x})}{2\sqrt{x}}\right)\;dx</m>; <m>u = \sqrt{x}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int 50(5x+1)^9\;dx</m>; <m>u=5x+1</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int e^x\sec^2(e^x+\pi)\;dx</m>; <m>u=e^x+\pi</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{3x^2}{2\sqrt{x^3+1}}\right)\;dx</m>; <m>u = x^3+1</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use <m>u</m>-substitution to integrate the following indefinite integrals.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{2x+1}{(x^2+x+1)^3}\right) \;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{x}{x^2+1}\right) \;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int xe^{-x^2} \;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int\tan(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    It will likely be helpful to remember that we can write <m>\tan(x)</m> as <m>\dfrac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}</m>. Now try to find an appropriate <m>u</m>-substitution.
                </p>
            </hint>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{1}{x\ln(x)}\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \sin^6(x)\cos(x)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int x\sec(x^2)\tan(x^2)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int \left(\frac{x}{1+x^4}\right)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    It will likely be helpful to rewrite this integral as:
                    <me>
                        \displaystyle\int \left(\frac{x}{1+(x^2)^2}\right)\;dx
                    </me>.
                    This isn't obvious!
                </p>
            </hint>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following definite integrals, identify a <m>u</m>-substitution and write the definite integral with regard to <m>u</m>, including new (translated) limits of integration.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=3} \left(\frac{1}{x+1}\right)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int_{\theta=\sqrt{\pi/2}}^{\theta=\sqrt{\pi}} \left(\theta\cos(\theta^2)\right)\;d\theta</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^{x=1} \left(x\sqrt{1-x^2}\right)\;dx</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\int_{t=-1}^{t=1} \left(\frac{2t+1}{\sqrt[3]{t^2+t+2}}\right)\;dt</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Evaluate all of the definite integrals above.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
</exercises>